});

// === 7) FAQ ===
const faqs=[
  {q:"What is tax loss harvesting?",a:"Tax loss harvesting is an investment strategy where you sell securities at a loss to offset capital gains taxes. You then reinvest in a similar (but not substantially identical) security to maintain your portfolio allocation. The harvested losses reduce your taxable income — up to $3,000 per year against ordinary income, with unlimited offset against capital gains. Unused losses carry forward indefinitely."},
  {q:"What is the wash sale rule?",a:"The wash sale rule (IRS Section 1091) prevents you from claiming a tax deduction on a security sold at a loss if you buy a substantially identical security within 30 days before or after the sale. This creates a 61-day window where you cannot repurchase the same investment. The disallowed loss gets added to the cost basis of the replacement security, deferring the benefit."},
  {q:"How much can tax loss harvesting save me?",a:"Savings depend on your capital gains, tax bracket, and available losses. At the highest federal rate (37% short-term / 20% long-term + 3.8% NIIT), harvesting $10,000 in short-term losses could save up to $4,080 in taxes. Even with no capital gains, you can deduct up to $3,000 in net losses against ordinary income each year, saving $720–$1,110 depending on your bracket."},
  {q:"What are common tax loss harvesting pairs?",a:"Common TLH pairs are funds that track similar but not identical indexes. Popular swaps: VTI → ITOT (US Total Market), VOO → IVV or SPLG (S&P 500), VXUS → IXUS (International), BND → AGG (US Bonds), VWO → IEMG (Emerging Markets). The key is swapping between Vanguard and iShares equivalents."},
  {q:"Can I tax loss harvest in a 401(k) or IRA?",a:"No. Tax loss harvesting only works in taxable brokerage accounts. Retirement accounts are already tax-advantaged. Be careful: buying a substantially identical security in your IRA within the wash sale window after selling at a loss in your taxable account can trigger the wash sale rule and permanently disallow the loss."},
  {q:"When is the best time to tax loss harvest?",a:"Year-round, not just December. Market dips create harvesting opportunities any time. Year-end is most common because investors review their full-year tax picture. The key is to harvest losses when available — waiting for year-end means missing mid-year volatility."},
  {q:"Does tax loss harvesting work for crypto?",a:"Yes, and crypto currently has an advantage: the wash sale rule does not apply to cryptocurrency as of 2026 (though legislation has been proposed). You can sell Bitcoin at a loss and immediately rebuy it to claim the deduction — something you cannot do with stocks or ETFs."},
  {q:"Is tax loss harvesting worth it for small portfolios?",a:"Yes. The $3,000 annual deduction against ordinary income works regardless of portfolio size. In the 24% bracket, that saves $720/year. Robo-advisors like Wealthfront and Betterment automate TLH at no extra cost, making it effortless for any account size. Losses also carry forward indefinitely, compounding the benefit over time."}
];
